This is normal behavior for MySql, because in this expression:

    Cat=&#39;hello&#39;

what happens is an *implicit conversion* of the string literal `&#39;hello&#39;` to `INTEGER` and as it is described in [Type Conversion in Expression Evaluation][1] the result of this conversion is `0`, so the expression is equivalent to:

    Cat=0
If you want to prevent this conversion you could instead convert the column `Cat` to string:

    WHERE CONVERT(Cat, CHAR) = &#39;hello&#39;
This way the comparison of `Cat` and `&#39;hello&#39;` will be alphanumerical and will fail.&lt;br/&gt;
But if you pass a valid integer, then the correct result will be returned.

  [1]: https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.7/en/type-conversion.html

